[Beaverton (population 89 803 residents in 2010) is a city in Washington County, in the US state of Oregon, located 7 miles (11 km) west of the city of Portland, making up the Portland metropolitan area; it is home to the world headquarters of Nike, Inc. (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beaverton,_Oregon). A map showing the area within 2 miles [3.2 km] of the intersection of Murray Boulevard and Scholls Ferry Road, where the 6 cases of Legionnaires' disease reside, can be found at https://www.google.com/maps/place/SW+Murray+Blvd+%26+SW+Scholls+Ferry+Rd,+Beaverton,+OR.

At this point, we do not know if we are dealing with a cluster of unrelated cases or a common-source outbreak, although 6 cases occurring within one week of each other within a 2-mile [3.2 km] radius suggest they are related. The investigation usually involves genotyping the clinical isolates of the bacterium _Legionella_ isolated from patients with Legionnaires' disease to establish whether this is a common source outbreak, if the genotypes of the clinical isolates match. However, if the diagnosis of Legionnaires' disease was based only on a positive urinary antigen assay, there will be no clinical isolates for genotyping. Matching the genotypes of clinical and environmental isolates of _Legionella_ will identify the environmental source for the individual cases. We will await further findings from the investigation.

Humans acquire Legionnaires' disease after exposure to natural or human-made aquatic reservoirs, usually by means of inhalation of aerosolized _Legionella_ bacteria, but the disease can also be acquired by aspiration of _Legionella_-contaminated potable water in people prone to aspirate, such as debilitated hospitalized patients. Possible person-to-person transmission of Legionnaires' disease has also been described by Correia et al (http://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMc1505356). _Legionella_ infection can be acquired less commonly by contamination of wounds.

Possible sources include aerosols generated from a _Legionella_-contaminated plumbing system by showerheads, sink faucets, cooling towers, decorative fountains, and hot tubs/spas. Warm water temperatures of 25-40 C (77-104 F) support the highest concentrations of the organism in plumbing systems. - Mod.ML

